   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "256ac590-0bbe-4009-993d-ac48437385a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Copying Sequences - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "04f67db3-206c-4010-b4c0-5875e44ff4bd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Why copy sequences?\n",
    "\n",
    "Mutable sequences can be modified.\n",
    "Sometimes you want to make sure that whatever sequence you work with cannot be modified by yourself or 3rd party functions.\n",
    "\n",
    "We saw example with concats and repetitions.\n",
    "Consider this example:\n",
    "\n",
    "def reverse(s):\n",
    "    s.reverse()\n",
    "    return s\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "new_list = reverse(s)\n",
    "\n",
    "new_list -> [30, 20, 10]\n",
    "s -> [30, 20, 10]\n",
    "\n",
    "We should have passed a copy of it.\n",
    "\n",
    "Soapbox of bad code (reverse function)\n",
    "Generally we write functions that don't modify contents of arguments.\n",
    "But sometimes we want to do that -> in-place methods\n",
    "However, to indicate to caller that something is happening in place we should not return the object\n",
    "If we don't return s then caller will wonder why not?\n",
    "So in this case the following would be a better approach.\n",
    "\n",
    "def reverse(s):\n",
    "    s.reverse()\n",
    "\n",
    "and if we don't do in place, then return reversed sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "def reverse(s):\n",
    "    s2 = <copy of s>\n",
    "    s2.reverse()\n",
    "    return s2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "446b4cc9-62a5-4059-ab5f-981963d58e89",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "How to copy a sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "We can copy using variety of methods\n",
    "s = [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "\n",
    "Simple loop\n",
    "cp = []\n",
    "for e in s:\n",
    "    cp.append(e)\n",
    "\n",
    "List Comprehension\n",
    "cp = [e for e in s]\n",
    "\n",
    "The copy method\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "Elements all point to the same objects in the list but list itself is a new object.\n",
    "Copy not implemented for immutables such as tuples or strings.\n",
    "\n",
    "Slicing\n",
    "cp = s[0:len(s)] or cp = s[:]\n",
    "\n",
    "List method\n",
    "list_2 = list(list_1)\n",
    "\n",
    "Note: tuple_2 = tuple(tuple_1) and t[:] get original tuple back; does not create a new tuple"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8ecdc7d4-6118-4fc4-af84-0e2559ce8aac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Watch out when copying entire immutable sequences\n",
    "\n",
    "l1 = [1, 2, 3]\n",
    "l2 = list(l1)\n",
    "\n",
    "l2 -> [1, 2, 3]\n",
    "id(l1) != id(l2)\n",
    "\n",
    "t1 = (1, 2, 3)\n",
    "t2 = tuple(t1)\n",
    "\n",
    "t2 -> (1, 2, 3)\n",
    "id(t1) = id(t2) (SAME OBJECT)\n",
    "\n",
    "t1 = (1, 2, 3)\n",
    "t2 = t1[:]\n",
    "\n",
    "t2 -> (1, 2, 3)\n",
    "id(t1) = id(t2) (SAME OBJECT)\n",
    "\n",
    "Same thing with strings, also immutable sequence type!\n",
    "Since sequence is immutable okay to return same sequence."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "334670a7-2a0b-490a-ab87-5d13c8e81bbb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Shallow Copies\n",
    "\n",
    "Using any techniques above, we have obtained a copy of the original sequence.\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "cp[0] = 100\n",
    "cp -> [100, 20, 30]\n",
    "s -> [10, 20, 30]\n",
    "\n",
    "Sequence safe from s will be safe from unintended modifications? Not quite.\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [[10, 20], [30, 40]]\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "cp[0] = 'python'\n",
    "cp -> ['python', [30, 40]]\n",
    "s -> [[10, 20], [30, 40]]\n",
    "cp[1][0] = 100\n",
    "cp -> ['python', [100, 40]]\n",
    "s -> [[10, 20], [100, 40]]\n",
    "\n",
    "What happened?\n",
    "When we use any copy methods, copy copies all object references from one sequence to another.\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [a, b]\n",
    "id(s) -> 1000, id(s[0]) -> 2000, id(s[1]) -> 3000\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "id(s) -> 5000, id(s[0]) -> 2000, id(s[1]) -> 3000\n",
    "\n",
    "When we made copy of s, sequence was copied but elements point to same memory address as original.\n",
    "The sequence was copied but elements were not. (Shallow)\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [1, 2]\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "cp.append(3)\n",
    "cp[1] = 3\n",
    "\n",
    "If elements of s are immutable, such as integers then not really important.\n",
    "But if elememts of s are mutable, then it can be important\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [[0, 0], [0, 0]]\n",
    "cp = s.copy()\n",
    "cp[0][0] = 100\n",
    "cp -> [[100, 0], [0, 0]]\n",
    "s -> [[100, 0], [0, 0]]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "2665cc9b-8052-47b1-bc1a-9aae5edf66ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Deep Copies\n",
    "\n",
    "So if collections contain mutable elements, shallow copies are not sufficient.\n",
    "Instead we have to do a deep copy. We can try\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [[0, 0], [0, 0]]\n",
    "cp = [e.copy() for e in s]\n",
    "\n",
    "Makes a copy first, then assigns copy to new element.\n",
    "cp is a copy of s, but also every element of cp is a copy of the corresponding element of s\n",
    "\n",
    "But what happens if the mutable elements of s themselves contain mutable elements\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [[[0, 1], [2, 3]], [[4, 5], [6, 7]]]\n",
    "\n",
    "We would need to make copies at least 3 levels deep to ensure deep copy.\n",
    "Deep copies need a recursive approach.\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep copies are not easy to do, You might have to deal with circular references.\n",
    "\n",
    "a = [10, 20]\n",
    "b = [a, 30]\n",
    "a.append(b)\n",
    "\n",
    "Circular references, infinite recursion.\n",
    "If you wrote your own deep copy algorithm you would need to handle circular references!\n",
    "\n",
    "In general, objects know how to make shallow copies themselves. \n",
    "Built in objects like lists, sets, and dictionaries dom they have a copy() method\n",
    "The standard library copy module has generic copy and deepcopy operations.\n",
    "\n",
    "Custom classes can implement the __copy__ and __deepcopy__ methods to allow you to override how shallow and deep copies are made for custom objects.\n",
    "Revisit this during OOP series of course."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "4e5ab853-1295-4443-94e3-3e6b6def6a03",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Deep Copies\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have custom class:\n",
    "\n",
    "def MyClass:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, a):\n",
    "        self.a = a\n",
    "\n",
    "from copy import copy, deepcopy\n",
    "\n",
    "x = [10, 20]\n",
    "obj = MyClass(x)\n",
    "x is obj.a -> True\n",
    "\n",
    "cp_shallow = copy(obj)\n",
    "cp_shallow.a is obj.a -> True\n",
    "\n",
    "cp_deep = deepcopy(obj)\n",
    "cp_deep.a is obj.a -> False"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f0b7b226-506f-43d6-80df-6cd011b45992",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Deep Copies\n",
    "\n",
    "def MyClass:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, a):\n",
    "        self.a = a\n",
    "\n",
    "x = MyClass(500)\n",
    "y = MyClass(x)\n",
    "y.a is x -> True\n",
    "\n",
    "lst = [x, y]\n",
    "there is a relationship between y.a and x\n",
    "\n",
    "cp = deepcopy(lst)\n",
    "cp[0] is x -> False\n",
    "cp[1] is y -> False\n",
    "cp[1].a is x -> False\n",
    "cp[1].a is cp[0] -> True\n",
    "\n",
    "Relationship between cp_y.a and cp_x is maintained!"
   ]
  },
